{"type":"assistant.message","data":{"messageId":"5415315e-0e3b-422b-8175-a9622535b17a","content":"## What Changed\n\nIn .NET 10 / C# 14, **implicit span conversions** now participate more broadly in overload resolution. For `array.Contains(num)` on an `int[]`, the compiler now resolves to:\n\n```\nMemoryExtensions.Contains<int>(this ReadOnlySpan<int>, int)\n```\n\ninstead of the previous:\n\n```\nEnumerable.Contains<int>(this IEnumerable<int>, int)\n```\n\nSince `ReadOnlySpan<T>` is a **ref struct**, it cannot be represented in expression trees. The expression tree interpreter (`preferInterpretation: true`) fails at runtime when it encounters the implicit `int[]` → `ReadOnlySpan<int>` conversion it cannot execute.\n\n## How to Fix\n\nExplicitly disambiguate to force the `Enumerable` overload:\n\n```csharp\n// Option 1: Call Enumerable.Contains as a static method\nExpression<Func<int[], int, bool>> expr =\n    (array, num) => Enumerable.Contains(array, num);\n\n// Option 2: Cast to IEnumerable<int> so the span overload is not applicable\nExpression<Func<int[], int, bool>> expr =\n    (array, num) => ((IEnumerable<int>)array).Contains(num);\n```\n\nEither approach ensures the expression tree references a method with no ref-struct parameters, which the interpreter can handle.","toolRequests":[],"interactionId":"95068253-3e4c-40da-b7ba-4ee47a1b4b04","reasoningOpaque":"","reasoningText":"The user is asking about a breaking change in .NET 10 / C# 14 that affects LINQ expression trees calling `.Contains()` on `int[]` arrays, specifically when compiled with `preferInterpretation: true`.\n\nLet me think about what changed in .NET 10 / C# 14 that would cause this.\n\nIn C# 14 / .NET 10, there's a significant change related to extension methods. C# 14 introduces **extension types** (formerly \"roles and extensions\"), but more relevantly, there's a change in how the compiler resolves `Contains` on arrays.\n\nActually, let me think more carefully. \n\nThe real culprit is probably that `MemoryExtensions.Contains` got prioritized over `Enumerable.Contains` for array types in .NET 10, or there's a new overload resolution that's causing the compiler to pick a different method when building expression trees. This could break interpretation if the expression tree compiler doesn't handle the new method signature the same way. the compiler is resolving `array.Contains(num)` to a different method in .NET 10 or C# 14, possibly one that doesn't work properly in expression trees at runtime. The span-based overload would fail at compile time due to ref struct restrictions, so it's likely a different optimization or method resolution change that's causing the runtime failure when `preferInterpretation: true` is used.\n\nWriting the fix...\n\nActually, I'm second-guessing myself here. Expression trees shouldn't even compile if they contain ref struct operations, so this should fail at compile time, not runtime. Unless the expression tree is being constructed manually with `Expression.Call` and the method resolution changed between compiler versions. But the user's code shows a lambda assigned directly to `Expression<Func<...>>`, which means the compiler is generating the tree, so it should catch this at compile time if it's truly a ref struct issue.\n\nLet me think about what actually changed in C# 14 or .NET 10 that could cause a runtime failure here. In .NET 10, arrays became implicitly convertible to `ReadOnlySpan<T>` in more contexts, which means `MemoryExtensions.Contains` now wins overload resolution over `Enumerable.Contains` for array arguments since the span version is more specific. The problem is that expression trees can't represent ref struct operations, so when the compiler tries to build an expression tree using the span method, it either fails at compile time or at runtime during interpretation. I'm reconsidering whether this is actually the root cause, since the compiler should catch ref struct issues earlier in the pipeline. Ah, that's it - there's a .NET 10 breaking change around implicit span conversions in overload resolution. Arrays can now implicitly convert to `ReadOnlySpan<T>`, which means `MemoryExtensions.Contains` becomes a viable candidate alongside `Enumerable.Contains`. The compiler prefers the span version in .NET 10, but expression trees can't represent span methods, so it fails to compile.\n\nBut the user says it throws at runtime, which suggests they might be building the expression tree dynamically through the Expression API rather than from a lambda, or there's something about how the tree gets interpreted that causes the failure later. The runtime interpreter might fail when trying to invoke `MemoryExtensions.Contains` with a span conversion, or alternatively `Enumerable.Contains` could have been modified in .NET 10 with annotations that affect how the interpreter handles it. I'm considering whether there's a change to how these methods are defined that would cause the expression tree interpreter to throw an exception.\n\nThe most plausible explanation is that C# 14's overload resolution now favors `MemoryExtensions.Contains` over `Enumerable.Contains` for arrays, and Roslyn's expression tree compiler emits a `MethodCallExpression` referencing the span-based overload, but the interpreter can't handle the implicit `int[]` to `ReadOnlySpan<int>` conversion at runtime since ref structs can't be properly materialized in that context.\n\nThe workarounds would be explicitly calling `Enumerable.Contains(array, num)` or casting the array to `IEnumerable<int>` first. Though I'm second-guessing whether the compiler would even allow a ref struct type in an expression tree at all—it might throw a compile-time error instead. But if the user is seeing a runtime error, they might be building the tree programmatically or there's something else going on. The timeline confirms it: .NET 9 introduced `params ReadOnlySpan<T>` and implicit span conversions that shifted overload resolution, making `MemoryExtensions.Contains` the preferred choice over `Enumerable.Contains` for arrays. This is the breaking change affecting expression trees in .NET 10 with C# 14. I'm seeing a compile-time error about expression trees not supporting ref struct types like `ReadOnlySpan<int>`. But the user described this as a runtime error, which makes me wonder if they're either mischaracterizing it or if there's a more subtle runtime issue happening after some workaround. Another angle: maybe in .NET 10, the BCL actually removed or changed `Enumerable.Contains<T>` for array types, replacing it with a span-based implementation, which would cause the MethodInfo lookup to fail at runtime when the expression tree tries to execute.\n\nThe most likely explanation is that C# 14 and .NET 10 expanded implicit span conversions in overload resolution, so `int[].Contains(int)` now prefers the `MemoryExtensions.Contains<int>` overload that takes a `ReadOnlySpan<int>` instead of the `Enumerable.Contains<int>` overload. Since ref structs can't be represented in expression trees, this either fails at compile time or throws when the expression tree interpreter encounters the span conversion at runtime. The solution is to explicitly call the `Enumerable` version to avoid the span conversion altogether.","outputTokens":4648,"requestId":"C430:C42E6:1E78DA6:2252951:6A07CB04"},"id":"b16aca51-68f6-44c8-96ec-11c8f3b09054","timestamp":"2026-05-16T01:41:39.699Z","parentId":"1cad7157-ab6f-403d-8365-23fa20d9aac7"}
